  "text": "TLS Configuration Architecture in Prometheus Stack:\n\nThe Prometheus monitoring stack enforces TLS configuration through a hierarchical architecture centered on the canonical TLSConfig struct defined in prometheus-common's config/http_config.go. This struct defines CA certificates, client certificates, server name verification, and insecure skip verify options.\n\n**TLS Struct Definition & Factory (prometheus-common):**\nThe TLSConfig struct (config/http_config.go:328) contains CAFile, CertFile, KeyFile, ServerName, and InsecureSkipVerify fields. The factory function NewTLSConfig (http_config.go:292) creates tls.Config objects from TLSConfig specifications, with support for CA file loading, client certificate validation, and dynamic CA file reloading via tlsRoundTripper.\n\n**Configuration Embedding Pattern:**\nAll external-facing components embed TLSConfig through HTTPClientConfig, which contains TLSConfig as a field (http_config.go:85). This embedded pattern propagates TLS configuration through:\n\n1. ScrapeConfig (config/config.go:728): HTTPClientConfig embedded for scrape target connections\n2. RemoteWriteConfig (config/config.go:1212): HTTPClientConfig embedded for remote write endpoints  \n3. RemoteReadConfig (config/config.go:1365): HTTPClientConfig embedded for remote read endpoints\n4. TracingConfig (config/config.go:925): Direct TLSConfig field for OTLP tracing exporters\n5. Discovery SDConfigs: All service discovery plugins (kubernetes, openstack, triton, etc.) embed HTTPClientConfig with TLSConfig\n\n**Server-Side TLS (Web Server):**\nPrometheus web server TLS is configured via web/web.go line 709, which calls toolkit_web.ServeMultiple with a FlagConfig pointing to the web.config.file parameter. This enables TLS server certificates and keys for the Prometheus HTTP API and UI. Main entry point (cmd/prometheus/main.go) reads the web config file and passes it through the Run method.\n\n**Client-Side TLS (Outbound Connections):**\n\n1. Scrape Target TLS: scrape/scrape.go:302 creates HTTP clients via config_util.NewClientFromConfig(cfg.HTTPClientConfig, ...), which applies TLSConfig to the http.Transport for scraping metrics from targets.\n\n2. Remote Write TLS: storage/remote/client.go and storage/remote/write.go:173 create write clients using NewClientFromConfig with the RemoteWriteConfig's HTTPClientConfig, enforcing TLS for sending metrics to remote endpoints.\n\n3. Remote Read TLS: storage/remote/client.go applies HTTPClientConfig TLS settings when creating clients for querying remote storage endpoints.\n\n4. Tracing TLS: tracing/tracing.go:189 (gRPC) and tracing/tracing.go:222 (HTTP) call config_util.NewTLSConfig(&tracingCfg.TLSConfig) to establish secure connections to OTLP tracing collectors. The gRPC client uses credentials.NewTLS with the tls.Config, while the HTTP client uses WithTLSClientConfig.\n\n**Service Discovery TLS:**\nAll service discovery plugins (kubernetes/kubernetes.go, openstack/openstack.go, triton/triton.go, etc.) inherit TLS support through their embedded HTTPClientConfig field, enabling secure communication with discovery endpoints (Kubernetes API, OpenStack endpoints, etc.).\n\n**TLS Validation (promtool):**\nThe promtool CLI (cmd/promtool/main.go:760) includes checkTLSConfig validation function that verifies TLS configurations are syntactically valid. This function is called during configuration validation for scrape configs (line 679) and service discovery configs (line 686), ensuring cert and key files are paired correctly.\n\n**Key Design Principles:**\n1. Centralized TLSConfig: Single definition in prometheus-common ensures consistency\n2. Composition over Inheritance: HTTPClientConfig composition pattern applies TLS everywhere HTTP is used\n3. File Path Support: SetDirectory() methods in config objects support relative file paths\n4. Validation at Load Time: Configuration unmarshalers validate TLS settings during YAML parsing\n5. Dynamic Reloading: TLS files can be reloaded without full process restart via tlsRoundTripper CA file monitoring\n\nThis architecture ensures TLS is enforced uniformly across all external interfaces: inbound (web API), outbound scraping, remote write/read, service discovery, and tracing exporters."
}

